/span></div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/CBmRQs0</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[clodivs]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>Today, several new laws come into force in Norway. One of these is a duty to label retouched advertising.</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/pE0vGQr</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/R4xdk5p.png" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>NOW RETAILED ADVERTISEMENT MUST BE MARKED
From today, advertisements and sponsored posts must be marked if they contain people who have had their skin or body shape changed. The mark itself is a visible white circle with the text «retouched person».</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/6e4kLON.png" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>WANTS TO AVOID BODY PRESSURE
According to Ministry of Children and Families Kjersti Toppe (Sp), the purpose of the new requirement is to counteract body pressure and unnatural body ideals.

- You should be aware of what is not natural, Toppe told VG earlier in June.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/P0CktQo.png" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>CLEAR FEEDBACK FROM YOUNG PEOPLE
Norway is one of the first countries in the world to introduce a requirement for the labeling of retouched advertising.

According to the Minister, the new rule should actually have several exceptions. But thanks to clear feedback from young people in the consultation round, the exceptions were scrapped.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/H2JKk5R.png" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>STRICTER REQUIREMENTS FOR COSMETIC INTERVENTIONS
Fighting body pressure is the purpose of another new decision.

Competence requirements have now been introduced to carry out certain forms of cosmetic procedures, injections and treatment. An age limit of 18 years has also been introduced for such non-medical interventions.
Source: https://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/i/g6oP50/dette-skjer-i-dag?fbclid=IwAR30SGK81MWSnEYfCNvoA-8OlnIPp3mo8xLJMTrPFA7IKEDz4wCJRqVqb4Y</div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/pE0vGQr</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[NaV3P]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>This could actually happen in the US...</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/fvhRujI</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/vmDNkxg.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>"In 1966, the leader of Romania, Nicolae Ceausescu, outlawed access to abortion and contraception in a bid to boost the country’s population. In the short term, it worked, and the year after it was enacted the average number of children born to Romanian women jumped from 1.9 to 3.7. But birthrates quickly fell again as women found ways around the ban. Wealthy, urban women were sometimes able to bribe doctors to perform abortions, or they had contraceptive IUDs smuggled in from Germany.

Romania’s prohibition of the procedure was disproportionately felt by low-income women and disadvantaged groups.

Many Romanian women turned to home and back-alley abortions, and by 1989, an estimated 10,000 women had died as a result of unsafe procedures. The real number of deaths might have been much higher, as women who sought abortions and those who helped them faced years of imprisonment if caught. Maternal mortality skyrocketed, doubling between 1965 and 1989."

